  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: af29c36912f2101449dddd2f477f6a71, type: 3}
  m_Name: 
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: Assembly-CSharp::DocumentationController
  contentText: {fileID: 1357447258}
  overviewButton: {fileID: 1827446541}
  geometryButton: {fileID: 1760693492}
  codeButton: {fileID: 1795834391}
  activeTabColor: {r: 0.5, g: 0.5, b: 0.5, a: 1}
  inactiveTabColor: {r: 1, g: 1, b: 1, a: 1}
  overviewInfo: 'The goal is to write code in the editor on the left to build a structure
    that perfectly matches the reference object on the right.


    After writing
    your code, press the <b>"Run Code"</b> button to see your creation. The score
    panel will show you how well you did.


    Use the different documentation tabs
    to learn about the geometry of the world and the basics of the coding language.'
  geometryInfo: 'The center of your build space is at the origin point <b>(0,0,0)</b>.


    Values
    for <color=red>x</color>, <color=green>y</color>, and <color=blue>z</color> can
    be negative or positive.


    Positive values extend towards the colored axis
    arrows.


    The grid has a size of <b>9x9x9</b>, which means coordinates range
    from <b>-4</b> to <b>4</b> on all axes.'
  codeInfo: 'Your task is to write a function called <b>PlaceVoxel(x, y, z)</b> that
    returns a block type number.


    <b>local c = 0</b>

    By default, the block
    type ''c'' is 0 (empty space).


    <b>if y == -4 then c = 1 end</b>

    Use
    <b>if</b> statements to assign a new value to ''c'' based on the coordinates.
    Later statements will overwrite earlier ones.


    <b>return c</b>

    At the
    end, the function must return the final value of ''c''.


    <b>Available Functions:</b>

    -
    math.abs(n) - Returns the absolute value of n.

    - math.sqrt(n) - Returns
    the square root of n.

    - math.sin(rad) - Returns the sine of an angle in
    radians.

    - math.cos(rad) - Returns the cosine of an angle in radians.'
